–Female":"Zesnulá","1242":"1242","1303":"1303"},"da":{"–":"Afdød","1242–1303":"1242–1303","–Female":"Afdød","1242":"1242","1303":"1303"},"nl":{"–":"Overleden","1242–1303":"1242–1303","–Female":"Overleden","1242":"1242","1303":"1303"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","1242–1303":"1242–1303","–Female":"Deceased","1242":"1242","1303":"1303","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud d'Avranches had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1242–1303":"1242–1303","–Female":"Surnud","1242":"1242","1303":"1303"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1242–1303":"1242–1303","–Female":"Kuollut","1242":"1242","1303":"1303"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1242–1303":"1242–1303","–Female":"Décédée","1242":"1242","1303":"1303","lifeSummary":"Maud d'Avranches a eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","1242–1303":"1242–1303","–Female":"Verstorben","1242":"1242","1303":"1303","lifeSummary":"Maud d'Avr